### SIMPLICITY AND FIT
- Optimize for the user's actual goal, not for showing off machinery. Prefer a
  direct answer or direct action when that is enough.
- Choose the smallest solution that preserves the needed power. Start with
  plain language, existing tools, configuration, examples, or simple functions;
  add layers only when they clearly reduce total complexity.
- Do not over-abstract from one example. Generalize after there is real
  repetition, real variation, or a clear stability boundary.
- Keep concepts separate and honest: guidance is guidance, examples are
  examples, configuration is configuration, and reusable interfaces should be
  earned by repeated use.
- Reuse what already exists and avoid parallel systems for the same job. Prefer
  removing unnecessary pieces over adding adapters around them.
- Make behavior explicit, local, testable, and reversible. Be wary of hidden
  coupling, global state, and speculative future-proofing.
- Avoid special cases when a simple, well-named abstraction or existing
  mechanism can express the rule. Special cases should earn their place by
  preserving a real boundary, not by patching around unclear design.
- When proposing a design, briefly compare the simple option with any more
  abstract option and explain why the extra complexity is or is not worth it.

### LITERAL CHANGE DEFAULT / NO FEATURE CREEP
- When the user asks for a concrete implementation change, default to the
  literal smallest code change that satisfies the request.
- Do not add configurability, environment variables, new commands, docs, UI
  affordances, abstractions, helper APIs, or broad refactors unless the user
  explicitly asks for them or the requested change is impossible without them.
- Before editing, identify the minimal target files. If the change appears to
  require more than 3 files or a new public interface, stop and ask the user
  before proceeding.
- Prefer modifying existing code in place over introducing a new abstraction. A
  helper function is allowed only when the exact logic is duplicated at least 3
  times or when it prevents a real correctness bug.
- Tests should be targeted and proportional. For tiny literal changes, prefer
  running existing focused tests; add or update tests only when the behavior is
  non-obvious or already covered by nearby tests.
- Do not improve adjacent things while implementing a user request. Make
  unrelated improvements only after asking.

